pages.content:
CL SDK provides a modular prompt system for building insurance-aware conversational agents. Prompts are composed from independent modules that adapt to the platform and communication intent.

## Quick start

```typescript

const ctx: AgentContext = {
  platform: "email",
  intent: "direct",
  siteUrl: "https://app.example.com",
  companyName: "Acme Insurance",
  userName: "Jane Smith",
};

const systemPrompt = buildAgentSystemPrompt(ctx);
// Use with any LLM: pass as the system message
```

## How it works

`buildAgentSystemPrompt(ctx)` composes all modules in order, filtering out any that return `null`:

```
Identity          → Who the agent is, company context
Company context   → Organization-specific information (if provided)
Intent            → Behavior rules for direct / mediated / observed
Formatting        → Platform-specific output rules
Safety            → Scope guardrails, anti-hallucination, prompt injection defense
Coverage gaps     → Gap detection guidance (null in some intents)
COI routing       → Certificate of insurance handling
Quotes/policies   → How to differentiate document types
Memory            → Cross-conversation continuity guidance
```

## AgentContext

The context object drives all prompt composition:

```typescript
interface AgentContext {
  platform: Platform;           // "email" | "chat" | "sms" | "slack" | "discord"
  intent: CommunicationIntent;  // "direct" | "mediated" | "observed"
  platformConfig?: PlatformConfig;
  companyName?: string;
  companyContext?: string;       // Organization-specific context string
  siteUrl: string;
  userName?: string;
  coiHandling?: "broker" | "user" | "member" | "ignore";
  brokerName?: string;
  brokerContactName?: string;
  brokerContactEmail?: string;
  agentName?: string;           // Display name (defaults to "CL-0 Agent")
  linkGuidance?: string;        // Custom link formatting guidance
}
```

## Individual modules

Each module is independently importable for custom prompt composition:

```typescript
  buildIdentityPrompt,
  buildSafetyPrompt,
  buildFormattingPrompt,
  buildCoverageGapPrompt,
  buildCoiRoutingPrompt,
  buildQuotesPoliciesPrompt,
  buildConversationMemoryGuidance,
  buildIntentPrompt,
} from "@claritylabs/cl-sdk";
```

### Custom composition

Build your own prompt from a subset of modules:

```typescript
const customPrompt = [
  buildIdentityPrompt(ctx),
  buildSafetyPrompt(ctx),
  buildFormattingPrompt(ctx),
  // Skip coverage gaps, COI routing, etc.
].filter(Boolean).join("\n\n");
```

## Document context

Build ranked document context for agent responses:

```typescript

const { context, relevantPolicyIds, relevantQuoteIds } =
  buildDocumentContext(policies, quotes, "What's my GL limit?");
// Returns policies/quotes ranked by relevance to the query
```

## Conversation memory

Add conversation history context:

```typescript

const memoryContext = buildConversationMemoryContext(previousConversations);
```

## Intent classification

Classify incoming messages before routing to the agent:

```typescript

const classificationPrompt = buildClassifyMessagePrompt("email");
// Returns a prompt that classifies whether a message is insurance-related
// and suggests an intent
```

CL SDK exports Claude `tool_use`-compatible tool schemas for common insurance agent operations. These are **schema-only** — CL SDK provides the definitions, and consumers implement the execution logic.

## Available tools

### Document Lookup

Search and retrieve insurance documents by ID, policy number, carrier, or free-text query.

```typescript
```

**Input schema:**

| Parameter | Type | Required | Description |
|-----------|------|----------|-------------|
| `id` | `string` | No | Exact document ID |
| `query` | `string` | No | Free-text search query |
| `documentType` | `"policy" \| "quote"` | No | Filter by document type |

### COI Generation

Request generation of a Certificate of Insurance for a specific policy.

```typescript
```

**Input schema:**

| Parameter | Type | Required | Description |
|-----------|------|----------|-------------|
| `policyId` | `string` | Yes | Policy ID to generate COI for |
| `holderName` | `string` | Yes | Certificate holder name |
| `holderAddress` | `string` | No | Certificate holder address |
| `additionalInsured` | `boolean` | No | Add holder as additional insured |

### Coverage Comparison

Compare coverages across two or more insurance documents.

```typescript
```

**Input schema:**

| Parameter | Type | Required | Description |
|-----------|------|----------|-------------|
| `documentIds` | `string[]` | Yes | Document IDs to compare |
| `coverageTypes` | `string[]` | No | Filter to specific coverage types |

## Using all tools

Import all tools as an array:

```typescript

// AGENT_TOOLS = [DOCUMENT_LOOKUP_TOOL, COI_GENERATION_TOOL, COVERAGE_COMPARISON_TOOL]
```

## Integration example

```typescript

const systemPrompt = buildAgentSystemPrompt(ctx);

const { text, toolCalls } = await generateText({
  model: yourModel,
  system: systemPrompt,
  tools: Object.fromEntries(
    AGENT_TOOLS.map(tool => [tool.name, {
      description: tool.description,
      parameters: tool.input_schema,
    }])
  ),
  messages: conversationHistory,
});

// Handle tool calls with your own implementations
for (const call of toolCalls) {
  switch (call.toolName) {
    case "document_lookup":
      // Query your database
      break;
    case "coi_generation":
      // Generate COI PDF
      break;
    case "coverage_comparison":
      // Build comparison table
      break;
  }
}
```

## ToolDefinition type

```typescript

interface ToolDefinition {
  name: string;
  description: string;
  input_schema: {
    type: "object";
    properties: Record<string, unknown>;
    required?: string[];
  };
}
```

## Pipeline functions

### `createExtractor(config)`

Create an extraction pipeline instance. Returns an object with a single `extract` method that processes a PDF and returns structured insurance data.

| Parameter | Type | Description |
|-----------|------|-------------|
| `config` | `ExtractorConfig` | Pipeline configuration (required) |

**Returns:** `{ extract(pdfBase64: string, documentId?: string): Promise<ExtractionResult> }`

```typescript

const extractor = createExtractor({
  generateText: myGenerateText,
  generateObject: myGenerateObject,
  onProgress: (msg) => console.log(msg),
  onTokenUsage: (usage) => console.log(`Tokens: ${usage.inputTokens} in, ${usage.outputTokens} out`),
});

const { document, chunks, tokenUsage, usageReporting } = await extractor.extract(pdfBase64);
```

The pipeline runs ten phases automatically:

1. **Classify** -- detect document type (policy/quote) and identify policy types, using the full PDF from `providerOptions.pdfBase64`
2. **Page map** -- map each page to focused extractors using page-scoped PDFs
3. **Plan** -- build deterministic extraction tasks from the page map and template hints
4. **Extract** -- dispatch focused extractors in parallel (concurrency-limited), with each worker receiving a page-scoped PDF from `extractPageRange()` via `providerOptions.pdfBase64` or `providerOptions.images`
5. **Review** -- check completeness and quality against template requirements, dispatch additional extractors for gaps (up to `maxReviewRounds`)
6. **Assemble** -- merge all extractor results into an `InsuranceDocument`
7. **Promote** -- fill top-level typed fields from declarations and coverages (carrier field mapping, broker, locations, loss payees, limits/deductibles synthesis, premium/total-cost fallback, taxes/fees synthesis)
8. **Summarize** -- generate a 1–3 sentence document summary via model call
9. **Format** -- clean up markdown formatting in content fields (pipe tables, space-aligned tables, sub-items, whitespace)
10. **Chunk** -- break the formatted document into `DocumentChunk[]` for vector storage

<Callout type="info">
  The `extract` method accepts an optional `documentId`. If omitted, a timestamped ID is generated automatically.
</Callout>

<Callout type="info">
  After the page-mapped extractor tasks complete, the coordinator also runs a full-document `supplementary` pass to capture hidden retrieval-only facts such as personal auto driver names, ages, DOBs, garaging details, and other structured key/value facts that do not belong in the strict primary schema.
</Callout>

---

### `chunkDocument(doc)`

Convert an `InsuranceDocument` into an array of `DocumentChunk` objects suitable for vector storage and retrieval.

| Parameter | Type | Description |
|-----------|------|-------------|
| `doc` | `InsuranceDocument` | The extracted document |

**Returns:** `DocumentChunk[]`

```typescript

const chunks = chunkDocument(document);
// Each chunk has: id, documentId, type, text, metadata
```

Chunk types include: `carrier_info`, `named_insured`, `coverage`, `definition`, `covered_reason`, `endorsement`, `exclusion`, `condition`, `section`, `declaration`, `loss_history`, `premium`, `supplementary`, `location`, `vehicle`, `classification`, `financial`, `party`, `subjectivity`, and `underwriting_condition`.

The `definition` and `covered_reason` chunk types make definitions, covered causes, inclusions, and attached covered-reason conditions independently retrievable. The `supplementary` chunk type includes both contact-style supplementary data and hidden retrieval-only facts from `document.supplementaryFacts`.

---

## Advanced -- Extractor definitions

These are low-level APIs for consumers who want to inspect or customize the extraction prompts.

### `getExtractor(name)`

Look up a focused extractor definition by name.

| Parameter | Type | Description |
|-----------|------|-------------|
| `name` | `string` | Extractor name (e.g. `"declarations"`, `"coverage_limits"`, `"definitions"`, `"covered_reasons"`, `"endorsements"`) |

**Returns:** `ExtractorDef | undefined`

```typescript

const ext = getExtractor("coverage_limits");
if (ext) {
  const prompt = ext.buildPrompt();
  // ext.schema is the Zod schema for the extractor's output
}
```

Available extractors: `carrier_info`, `named_insured`, `declarations`, `coverage_limits`, `definitions`, `covered_reasons`, `endorsements`, `exclusions`, `conditions`, `premium_breakdown`, `loss_history`, `sections`, and `supplementary`.

---

### `getTemplate(policyType)`

Get the line-of-business template for a given policy type. Templates define what sections the extraction pipeline expects and where to find them.

| Parameter | Type | Description |
|-----------|------|-------------|
| `policyType` | `string` | A `PolicyType` value (e.g. `"commercial_auto"`, `"workers_comp"`, `"cyber"`) |

**Returns:** `DocumentTemplate`

```typescript

const template = getTemplate("workers_comp");
// template.expectedSections: ["declarations", "coverage", "endorsements", ...]
// template.required: ["declarations", "coverage"]
// template.pageHints: { declarations: "Usually pages 1-3", ... }
```

---

## Configuration types

### `ExtractorConfig`

```typescript
interface ExtractorConfig {
  /** Provider callback for text generation */
  generateText: GenerateText;
  /** Provider callback for structured output with Zod schemas */
  generateObject: GenerateObject;
  /** Optional PDF-to-images converter. When provided, pages are sent as images instead of native PDF */
  convertPdfToImages?: ConvertPdfToImagesFn;
  /** Maximum parallel extractor dispatch (default: 2) */
  concurrency?: number;
  /** Maximum review/re-extraction rounds (default: 2) */
  maxReviewRounds?: number;
  /** Called after each model call with token counts */
  onTokenUsage?: (usage: TokenUsage) => void;
  /** Called with human-readable progress messages during extraction */
  onProgress?: (message: string) => void;
  /** Optional async logger */
  log?: LogFn;
  /** Pass-through provider options forwarded to every model call.
   *  For extraction, this is also where the coordinator/worker pipeline passes PDF or image content to your callback.
   */
  providerOptions?: Record<string, unknown>;
}
```

### `ExtractionResult`

```typescript
interface ExtractionResult {
  /** The fully assembled insurance document */
  document: InsuranceDocument;
  /** Pre-computed chunks ready for vector storage */
  chunks: DocumentChunk[];
  /** Aggregate token usage across all model calls */
  tokenUsage: TokenUsage;
  /** Whether provider callbacks actually returned usage for each model call */
  usageReporting: {
    modelCalls: number;
    callsWithUsage: number;
    callsMissingUsage: number;
  };
}
```

`ExtractionResult.document` may include `definitions?: Definition[]`, `coveredReasons?: CoveredReason[]`, and `supplementaryFacts?: Array<{ key: string; value: string; subject?: string; context?: string }>` when the relevant extractors find those records.

### `ExtractorDef`

```typescript
interface ExtractorDef {
  /** Build the extraction prompt for this domain */
  buildPrompt(): string;
  /** Zod schema for validating the extractor's output */
  schema: ZodSchema;
  /** Optional max tokens override for this extractor */
  maxTokens?: number;
}
```

### `DocumentTemplate`

```typescript
interface DocumentTemplate {
  /** Sections the pipeline expects to extract */
  expectedSections: string[];
  /** Hints about where sections typically appear in the PDF */
  pageHints: Record<string, string>;
  /** Sections that must be present for a complete extraction */
  required: string[];
  /** Sections that are extracted if found but not required */
  optional: string[];
}
```

### `TokenUsage`

```typescript
interface TokenUsage {
  inputTokens: number;
  outputTokens: number;
}
```

### `LogFn`

```typescript
type LogFn = (message: string) => Promise<void>;
```

---

## Schema utilities

### `toStrictSchema(schema)`

Transform a Zod schema for strict structured output compatibility. Recursively converts `.optional()` properties to `.nullable()` so all properties appear in the JSON Schema `required` array.

| Parameter | Type | Description |
|-----------|------|-------------|
| `schema` | `ZodTypeAny` | Any Zod schema |

**Returns:** `ZodTypeAny` — the transformed schema

```typescript

const strict = toStrictSchema(z.object({
  name: z.string(),
  age: z.number().optional(), // becomes z.number().nullable()
}));
```

<Callout type="info">
  You don't need to call this yourself — the pipeline applies it automatically before every `generateObject` call. It's exported for consumers building custom pipelines.
</Callout>

---

### `safeGenerateObject(generateObject, params, options?)`

Wraps a `generateObject` call with schema strictification, retry on transient errors, and optional fallback values.

| Parameter | Type | Description |
|-----------|------|-------------|
| `generateObject` | `GenerateObject<T>` | Your provider callback |
| `params` | `{ prompt, schema, maxTokens, ... }` | Same params as `generateObject` |
| `options.fallback` | `T` | Return this value if all retries fail (optional) |
| `options.maxRetries` | `number` | Schema validation retries, default 1 |
| `options.log` | `LogFn` | Logger for retry status messages |

**Returns:** `Promise<{ object: T; usage?: TokenUsage }>`

If you use `safeGenerateObject()` in your own extraction flow, make sure you continue to pass through `providerOptions.pdfBase64` or `providerOptions.images` to your provider callback.

```typescript

const { object } = await safeGenerateObject(
  myGenerateObject,
  { prompt: "...", schema: MySchema, maxTokens: 1024 },
  {
    fallback: { status: "unknown" },
    maxRetries: 2,
  },
);
```

## Pipeline functions

### `createQueryAgent(config)`

Create a query agent that answers questions against stored documents with citation-backed provenance.
It also supports per-query multimodal attachments such as photos, PDFs, and raw text snippets.

| Parameter | Type | Description |
|-----------|------|-------------|
| `config` | `QueryConfig` | Pipeline configuration (see below) |

**Returns:** `{ query(input: QueryInput) => Promise<QueryOutput> }`

```typescript

const agent = createQueryAgent({
  generateText,
  generateObject,
  documentStore,
  memoryStore,
  concurrency: 3,
  maxVerifyRounds: 1,
  retrievalLimit: 10,
});
```

---

### `agent.query(input)`

Run the full query pipeline: classify, retrieve, reason, verify, respond.

| Parameter | Type | Description |
|-----------|------|-------------|
| `input.question` | `string` | The user's question |
| `input.conversationId` | `string?` | Conversation ID for history context |
| `input.context` | `AgentContext?` | Platform and user context |
| `input.attachments` | `QueryAttachment[]?` | Optional inbound files or text context to interpret and combine with stored evidence |

**Returns:** `Promise<QueryOutput>`

```typescript
const result = await agent.query({
  question: "What is the deductible on our GL policy?",
  conversationId: "conv-123",
});

console.log(result.answer);      // Natural language answer with [1], [2] citations
console.log(result.citations);   // Citation[] with source references
console.log(result.confidence);  // 0-1 confidence score
console.log(result.intent);      // "policy_question"
console.log(result.followUp);    // Optional follow-up suggestion
console.log(result.tokenUsage);  // { inputTokens, outputTokens }
console.log(result.reviewReport); // Deterministic grounding/citation quality report
```

### Multimodal example

```typescript
const result = await agent.query({
  question: "What else do we need to know about this, and does it match the stored policy?",
  conversationId: "conv-123",
  attachments: [
    {
      kind: "image",
      name: "wall-damage.jpg",
      mimeType: "image/jpeg",
      base64: damagePhotoBase64,
      description: "Photo the tenant texted in",
    },
    {
      kind: "pdf",
      name: "coi.pdf",
      mimeType: "application/pdf",
      base64: coiPdfBase64,
    },
    {
      kind: "text",
      name: "email-context",
      text: "Carrier asked whether the certificate holder needs waiver of subrogation.",
    },
  ],
});
```

---

## Types

### `QueryConfig`

```typescript
interface QueryConfig {
  generateText: GenerateText;
  generateObject: GenerateObject;
  documentStore: DocumentStore;
  memoryStore: MemoryStore;
  concurrency?: number;           // default: 3
  maxVerifyRounds?: number;       // default: 1
  retrievalLimit?: number;        // default: 10
  onTokenUsage?: (usage: TokenUsage) => void;
  onProgress?: (message: string) => void;
  log?: LogFn;
  providerOptions?: Record<string, unknown>;
  qualityGate?: "off" | "warn" | "error";
}
```

### `QueryInput`

```typescript
interface QueryInput {
  question: string;
  conversationId?: string;
  context?: AgentContext;
  attachments?: QueryAttachment[];
}
```

### `QueryAttachment`

```typescript
interface QueryAttachment {
  id?: string;
  kind: "image" | "pdf" | "text";
  name?: string;
  mimeType?: string;
  base64?: string;      // image/pdf content
  text?: string;        // text attachment content
  description?: string; // optional caller hint
}
```

### `QueryOutput`

```typescript
interface QueryOutput {
  answer: string;
  citations: Citation[];
  intent: QueryIntent;
  confidence: number;
  followUp?: string;
  tokenUsage: TokenUsage;
  reviewReport: QueryReviewReport;
}
```

### `Citation`

```typescript
interface Citation {
  index: number;
  chunkId: string;
  documentId: string;
  documentType?: "policy" | "quote";
  field?: string;
  quote: string;
  relevance: number;
}
```

### `QueryIntent`

```typescript
type QueryIntent =
  | "policy_question"
  | "coverage_comparison"
  | "document_search"
  | "claims_inquiry"
  | "general_knowledge";
```

---

## Query prompt functions

These are exported for advanced use (custom pipelines, testing):

### `buildQueryClassifyPrompt(question, conversationContext?, attachmentContext?)`

Build the classification prompt for intent detection and sub-question decomposition.

### `buildInterpretAttachmentPrompt(question, attachment)`

Build the attachment interpretation prompt used for inbound image/PDF/text context.

### `buildReasonPrompt(subQuestion, intent, evidence)`

Build an intent-specific reasoning prompt with evidence context.

### `buildVerifyPrompt(originalQuestion, subAnswersJson, evidenceJson)`

Build the verification prompt for grounding, consistency, and completeness checks.

### `buildRespondPrompt(originalQuestion, subAnswersJson, platform?)`

Build the final response formatting prompt with platform-specific formatting guidance.

## Provider callback requirements for attachments

The query agent can pass multimodal payloads through `providerOptions` when attachments are present:

- `providerOptions.attachments` for the raw attachment list
- `providerOptions.pdfBase64` for PDF attachments
- `providerOptions.images` for image attachments

Your `generateObject` callback must translate those fields into actual provider-specific file or image parts. If it does not, attachment-aware queries will silently degrade into text-only behavior.

CL SDK provides PDF page utilities plus two modes for writing data onto PDFs using `pdf-lib`: **AcroForm filling** for fillable PDFs and **text overlay** for flat/scanned PDFs.

## Page utilities

Extract page ranges or get page counts without full parsing — useful for reducing token usage.

```typescript

// Get page count
const totalPages = await getPdfPageCount(pdfBase64);

// Extract only the declarations pages (pages 1-5) for classification
const declsOnly = await extractPageRange(pdfBase64, 1, 5);

// Returns the original if the range covers all pages
const same = await extractPageRange(pdfBase64, 1, totalPages);
```

## AcroForm fields

### Detect fields

Enumerate all fillable form fields in a PDF:

```typescript

const pdfDoc = await PDFDocument.load(pdfBytes);
const fields = getAcroFormFields(pdfDoc);

// [
//   { name: "insured_name", type: "text" },
//   { name: "agree_terms", type: "checkbox" },
//   { name: "state", type: "dropdown", options: ["CA", "NY", "TX"] },
// ]
```

Returns an empty array if the PDF has no AcroForm.

**Field types:** `text`, `checkbox`, `dropdown`, `radio`

### Fill and flatten

Fill AcroForm fields by name and flatten the form (makes fields non-editable):

```typescript

const mappings: FieldMapping[] = [
  { acroFormName: "insured_name", value: "Acme Corp" },
  { acroFormName: "effective_date", value: "01/01/2025" },
  { acroFormName: "agree_terms", value: "yes" },  // checks the checkbox
  { acroFormName: "state", value: "CA" },          // selects dropdown option
];

const filledPdfBytes = await fillAcroForm(pdfBytes, mappings);
```

**Checkbox values:** `"yes"`, `"true"`, `"x"`, `"checked"`, `"on"` check the box. Anything else unchecks it.

Fields not found in the PDF or values not in dropdown/radio options are silently skipped.

## Text overlay

For flat or scanned PDFs without form fields, overlay text at specific coordinates:

```typescript

const overlays: TextOverlay[] = [
  {
    page: 0,          // 0-indexed page number
    x: 25.5,          // percentage from left edge (0-100)
    y: 15.2,          // percentage from top edge (0-100)
    text: "Acme Corp",
    fontSize: 10,
  },
  {
    page: 0,
    x: 60,
    y: 30,
    text: "",
    isCheckmark: true,  // Draws an "X" instead of text
    fontSize: 12,
  },
];

const overlaidPdfBytes = await overlayTextOnPdf(pdfBytes, overlays);
```

### Coordinate system

- **`x`** — percentage from the left edge (0 = left, 100 = right)
- **`y`** — percentage from the top edge (0 = top, 100 = bottom)
- Coordinates are converted internally to pdf-lib's bottom-left origin system

### TextOverlay type

```typescript
interface TextOverlay {
  page: number;       // 0-indexed page number
  x: number;          // percentage from left (0-100)
  y: number;          // percentage from top (0-100)
  text: string;
  fontSize?: number;  // default: 10
  isCheckmark?: boolean;
}
```

Overlays for pages that don't exist are silently skipped.

CL SDK uses plain callback functions instead of framework-specific model objects. You provide functions that call your preferred LLM provider, and the SDK handles orchestration, retries, and concurrency. No framework dependency required.

## Callback types

There are four callback types. Only `generateText` and `generateObject` are required for all pipelines:

```typescript
// Required — used by all pipelines (extraction, query, application)
type GenerateText = (params: {
  prompt: string;
  system?: string;
  maxTokens: number;
  providerOptions?: Record<string, unknown>;
}) => Promise<{ text: string; usage?: TokenUsage }>;

type GenerateObject<T = unknown> = (params: {
  prompt: string;
  system?: string;
  schema: ZodSchema<T>;
  maxTokens: number;
  providerOptions?: Record<string, unknown>;
}) => Promise<{ object: T; usage?: TokenUsage }>;

// Required for MemoryStore (vector search over chunks)
type EmbedText = (text: string) => Promise<number[]>;

// Optional — enables vision-based extraction (PDF pages as images)
type ConvertPdfToImagesFn = (
  pdfBase64: string,
  startPage: number,
  endPage: number,
) => Promise<Array<{ imageBase64: string; mimeType: string }>>;
```

For extraction and multimodal query calls, `providerOptions` is also the document transport layer:

- `providerOptions.pdfBase64` carries the PDF to include as a file/document part
- `providerOptions.images` carries rendered page images to include as image parts
- `providerOptions.attachments` carries generic query attachments such as inbound photos, PDFs, and text snippets
- classify and plan receive the full PDF
- worker extractors receive a page-scoped PDF produced by `extractPageRange()`, unless `convertPdfToImages` is enabled
- query attachment interpretation calls may set both `providerOptions.attachments` and the convenience fields above for the current attachment

## Provider examples

<Tabs items={["Anthropic", "OpenAI", "Vercel AI SDK"]}>
  <Tab value="Anthropic">
    ```typescript
    import Anthropic from "@anthropic-ai/sdk";

    const client = new Anthropic();

    const generateText = async ({ prompt, system, maxTokens, providerOptions }) => {
      const response = await client.messages.create({
        model: "claude-sonnet-4-6",
        max_tokens: maxTokens,
        system: system ? [{ type: "text", text: system }] : undefined,
        messages: [{ role: "user", content: prompt }],
      });
      return {
        text: response.content[0].type === "text" ? response.content[0].text : "",
        usage: {
          inputTokens: response.usage.input_tokens,
          outputTokens: response.usage.output_tokens,
        },
      };
    };

    const generateObject = async ({ prompt, system, schema, maxTokens, providerOptions }) => {
      const response = await client.messages.create({
        model: "claude-sonnet-4-6",
        max_tokens: maxTokens,
        system: system ? [{ type: "text", text: system }] : undefined,
        messages: [{
          role: "user",
          content: [
            ...(providerOptions?.pdfBase64
              ? [{ type: "document", source: { type: "base64", media_type: "application/pdf", data: providerOptions.pdfBase64 } }]
              : []),
            ...((providerOptions?.attachments as Array<{
              kind: "image" | "pdf" | "text";
              name?: string;
              mimeType?: string;
              base64?: string;
              text?: string;
            }> | undefined)?.flatMap((attachment) => {
              if (attachment.kind === "pdf" && attachment.base64) {
                return [{
                  type: "document" as const,
                  source: { type: "base64" as const, media_type: attachment.mimeType ?? "application/pdf", data: attachment.base64 },
                }];
              }
              if (attachment.kind === "image" && attachment.base64) {
                return [{
                  type: "image" as const,
                  source: { type: "base64" as const, media_type: attachment.mimeType ?? "image/jpeg", data: attachment.base64 },
                }];
              }
              if (attachment.kind === "text" && attachment.text) {
                return [{ type: "text" as const, text: attachment.text }];
              }
              return [];
            }) ?? []),
            ...((providerOptions?.images as Array<{ imageBase64: string; mimeType: string }> | undefined)?.map((img) => ({
              type: "image",
              source: { type: "base64", media_type: img.mimeType, data: img.imageBase64 },
            })) ?? []),
            { type: "text", text: prompt },
          ],
        }],
      });
      const text = response.content[0].type === "text" ? response.content[0].text : "{}";
      return {
        object: schema.parse(JSON.parse(text)),
        usage: {
          inputTokens: response.usage.input_tokens,
          outputTokens: response.usage.output_tokens,
        },
      };
    };
    ```
